05859nam a22008535i 9783110899016DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20122005gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013967498  a97831108990167 a10.1515/97831108990162doi  a(DE-B1597)56608  a(OCoLC)840440614  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPA6519.M9bP37 2005 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a871  aFX 1914052rvk0(DE-625)rvk/35174:117841 aPapaioannou, Sophia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEpic Succession and Dissension :bOvid, Metamorphoses 13.623-14.582, and the Reinvention of the Aeneid /cSophia Papaioannou. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2012] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUntersuchungen zur antiken Literatur und Geschichte ,x1862-1112 ;v7300ti-vi -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tSummary of the ‘little Aeneid’ (Ovid, Met. 13.623-14.582) -- tChapter One Aeneads and Aniads: Offering Politics and the Politics of Offering, or Narrative Discourse on Anius' Crater (Met. 13.681-701) -- tChapter Two Immortality and Mutability: The Sibyl and the Power of Poetic Memory -- tChapter Three Centralizing the Marginal: The Anamorphosis of Achaemenides -- tChapter Four Marginalizing the Central: Macareus' Anamnesis -- tChapter Five Experimentation on a Narrative Chain I: Poetology, Epic Definition, and the Near-Swans of Diomedes -- tChapter Six Experimentation on a Narrative Chain II: Vergilian Ships and Ovidian Nymphs, and a Play of Literary Identities -- tChapter Seven Epic Conclusion and Epic Closure: The Fall of Ardea -- tBibliography -- tIndexes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHiermit liegt die erste ausführliche, neuzeitliche und kritische Analyse von Ovids Metamorphosen 13.623-14.582 vor. Ovid setzte hier neue Maßstäbe in Bezug auf epische Poesie und die Art ihrer Rezeption. Zunächst wird die methodologische Komplexität von Ovids 'Umarmungsstrategie' vorgestellt, daran anschließend diskutiert Papaioannou in einer genauen Untersuchung der 'kleinen Aeneis' das dichte Netz von Anspielungen auf das Original, legt die Struktur und die Themen jeder Episode aus und zeigt prominente Motive in den Metamorphosen auf. Nicht zuletzt werden die poetischen Techniken der Metamorphosen erkundet, wobei Papaioannou argumentiert, Ovid reproduziere den Geist und die Grundzüge des Originals durch seine selektive Einbettung der Aeneis auf sehr durchdachte, idiosynkratische Weise.  aThis study constitutes the first modern book-length, in-depth critical analysis of Ovid, Metamorphoses 13.623–14.582. In this unit Ovid, by challenging openly the artistry of his great predecessor Vergil, redraws the parameters associated with the definition and appreciation of epic poetry. The book first introduces the methodological complexity of the Ovidian embrace strategy, and, subsequently, it reads the ‘little Aeneid’ closely, discussing the network of allusions to its prototype. It assesses the structure and thematics of each episode in the cluster, and traces the recurrence of prominent motifs throughout the Metamorphoses. Not least, it explores poetics, arguing that Ovid’s selective incorporation of the Aeneid reproduces the spirit and fundamental ideas of the model in an idiosyncratic sophisticated manner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLatin literature. 4aAeneis. 4aMetamorphosen. 4aOvid. 4aVergil. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014